data.name: Brih
data.operations: <p>Vehicles: 1 municipal pick-up, no compaction. No scale.<br /> Frequency: Every day door-to-door collection of all waste<br /> Single facility. Land rented. Concrete and roof, without walls.<br /> Recyclables: Secondary sorting, separation by products (cans, batteries, bulbs). No compaction yet.<br /> Compost: Table for bag removal and sorting, shredder available, addition of saw dust for moisture, daily or every other day rotation, 21 days composting, followed by maturation. Temperature monitoring on a daily basis for each pile.<br /> Residual: Diapers in sanitary hole adjacent to facility, other to pyrolysis unit?</p>
data.outtype: compost, recyclables, batteries, light bulbs, residual
data.summary: Initiated in December 2016, the municipal collection, sorting and treatment services accomade daily between 0,5 and 1 ton of waste. Organic waste is composted, recyclables are sorted and residuals are sent away. Diversion from landfill is around 80%.

data.name: Beit Mery
data.contact: Municipality of Beit Mery, Cedar Environmental (Ziad Abi Chaker)
data.operations: <p>Households: 2-colored-bag system (since oct-2016), disposing of in road containers<br /> Vehicles: Trucks without compaction collecting all waste.<br /> Frequency: Every day collection of all waste.<br /> Single facility, 5000sqm, 20 workers daily. Scale at entrance. <br /> Recyclables: manual separation on conveyor, separation in 7 fractions, including electronic waste, textiles; Compactor available.<br /> Compost: in rotating drum for 3 days, followed by open air maturation phase, including paper and diapers. Continuous temperature monitoring in drum. Screening and bagging after maturation.<br /> Residual: soft plastics and packaging used as eco-board</p>
data.summary: In October 2016, the Municipality of Beit Mery and Cedar Environmental inaugurated a sorting and composting facility on the location of a former dump (Monteverde) which had been re-used during the 2015-2016 crisis. The facility has the highest recycling rate in the country thanks to patented technology from Cedar Environmental, and was awared in October 2017, the Green Business of the Year award by Lebanon Opportunities.

data.name: Naameh Landfill
data.operations: <p>Sanitary landfill operated from 1998 to 2015, by Sukomi, under supervision of Laceco, for the Government of Lebanon, represented by the CDR.<br /> Total capacity: 15 million tons (est.)<br /> Structure: several cells with geomembrane, leachate collection pipes, and final capping to be set in 2017.<br /> Leachate: two collection points, with undercapacity of treatment and raw discharge near Ghadir river mouth.<br /> Methane: collection of landfill gas and power generation around 6 MW (since 12/2016) after some years of testing.</p>
data.outtype: leachate, methane, carbon dioxide, GHG, electricity

data.name: Bourj Hammoud Landfill
data.operations:
Sanitary landfill in operation since 10/2016, by Khoury Contracting, under supervision of Laceco, for the Governement of Lebanon, represented by the CDR.
Total capacity: 1,2 million tons (according to initial plans), expected to be full in 08/2018.
Structure: four cells built in the sea using the formel Bourj Hammoud dumpsite as backfill, with geomenbranes, leachates collection pipes and dikes.
Leachate: expected to be pumped out from the cells and treated by a reverse osmosis unit (imported from Germany) before discharge of water in the sea. As for 02/2017, this system is not yet operational.
Methane: collection of landfill gas not planned before final capping, no power generation planned.

data.name: L'Ecoute
data.operations:
1-Collection: It is done on the basis of a routine ranging from bi-weekly to monthly, as needed. The vans of the association ensure the collection of the material at the home of the interested persons or within the companies. 
2-Sorting: the waste is then sent to the sorting center of the association and divided according to their category. 
3-Routing to recycling centers: After sorting, the recovered and categorized material is then sent to recycling plants where it will be sold.

*Electricity recycling also provides the following services: 
· Disassembly of various electronic objects intended for scrapping (computers, household appliances, ..) in order to recover raw materials. 
· Reconditioning failed appliances to redistribute them to needy people
data.summary: L’Ecoute was created as an NGO in 1999 with a purpose to collect household and industrial waste, sorts it, and routes it to recycling centers.

data.operations:
The process consists of the following simple steps:
The consumer gathers his/her electronic waste, locates the closest collection point from the list that was previously provided to him/her, and drops them off.
The electronic waste is later collected by trucks provided by Beeatoona, ensuring a safe disposal of the collected material in a special warehouse, as a preliminary step to the recycling process.
data.summary: Beeatoona has launched a project for battery recycling in schools of Lebanon, Jordan and Tunisia. Their aim is to engage students of 50 schools in each of Lebanon, Tunisia, and Jordan in the sorting and collecting of household batteries and designing awareness material regarding recycling of batteries.
